John Edward: Linguistic Competences are Fundamental to the World’s Citizens
The independent educational centers in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes harvested in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, he comes to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you can’t depend solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can observe that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest approved rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages got an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students got an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also got an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them as a fundamental competition that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as the subjects of CTEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK’s Employment and Competence Commission revealed that, for the reasons given by employers about the difficulties they encountered in covering jobs, 17 % were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
The potential job opportunities that languages require are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the race someone chooses, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real edge in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance to the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation. Also, it was established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If you know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you will always be able to choose from several languages taught by specialized teaching staff in this field.
The independent educational centres in Scotland dedicate all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future may hold for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “competences for international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
