Red tide update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission’s new report shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Over the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and on its coast, low and high concentrations on the Hillsborough County coast, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, bottom to mid concentrations in Charlotte County, and in Charlotte County.
Respiratory problems are still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory problems have been reported in the northwestern Florida area over the past week.
